00:00:22.388 --> 00:00:24.430
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Let
me just introduce myself.

00:00:24.430 --> 00:00:27.820
And then maybe you all
can introduce yourselves

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:30.790
to me and to each other.

00:00:30.790 --> 00:00:32.409
So I'm Bill Bonvillian.

00:00:32.409 --> 00:00:37.450
And for the last 11 years,
I have been director

00:00:37.450 --> 00:00:40.630
of MIT's Washington DC office.

00:00:40.630 --> 00:00:44.560
And I've taught at
Georgetown University

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:49.810
a course on science and tech
policy for about 12 years.

00:00:49.810 --> 00:00:54.880
And I teach a different course
on energy technology policy

00:00:54.880 --> 00:00:56.110
at Johns Hopkins SAIS.

00:00:56.110 --> 00:01:01.435
So I'm on the edge on faculty
at Georgetown and Hopkins SAIS.

00:01:04.030 --> 00:01:07.120
And after 11 years of being
director of the Washington

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:09.010
office, I've stepped
down from that job.

00:01:09.010 --> 00:01:11.170
So I'm now a lecturer up here.

00:01:11.170 --> 00:01:15.110
And I've got an attachment
to MIT's Industrial Policy

00:01:15.110 --> 00:01:19.290
Center, which is one
of its policy centers.

00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:23.580
And I'm finishing my
third book actually,

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:26.950
which is now at MIT press
on advanced manufacturing.

00:01:26.950 --> 00:01:29.560
So you're going to hear
more than your share

00:01:29.560 --> 00:01:32.380
about manufacturing
for this all over.

00:01:32.380 --> 00:01:34.030
You're stuck with
those realities.

00:01:36.580 --> 00:01:41.920
And I had a background in--

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:45.460
I was in the executive
branch as a child.

00:01:45.460 --> 00:01:48.460
And I was a Deputy Assistant
Secretary of Transportation

00:01:48.460 --> 00:01:50.110
in my youth long
before any of you

00:01:50.110 --> 00:01:53.530
were born and got
to really engage

00:01:53.530 --> 00:01:55.780
in the development
of major legislation

00:01:55.780 --> 00:01:59.740
that deregulated most of the
big transportation sectors.

00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:02.050
So aviation, trucking,
and railroads and then

00:02:02.050 --> 00:02:05.560
did a lot of work on
surface transportation.

00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:09.280
And then practiced law because
I've been trained as a lawyer.

00:02:09.280 --> 00:02:11.170
So I practiced law for a decade.

00:02:11.170 --> 00:02:15.340
And then somebody I knew and
had worked with at an earlier

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:17.050
stage became US senator.

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:21.790
So I get one of those proverbial
Washington phone calls--

00:02:21.790 --> 00:02:24.970
why don't you come up
and we'll talk, Bill?

00:02:24.970 --> 00:02:27.470
And that conversation
lasted for over 15 years.

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:29.770
So I couldn't resist
staying up there.

00:02:29.770 --> 00:02:32.770
It was much too
interesting and fun.

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:37.840
So I had a long career
working in the US senate

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:39.490
and worked on lots
of legislation

00:02:39.490 --> 00:02:43.930
but including a lot of work on
innovation policy and science

00:02:43.930 --> 00:02:46.630
policy and R&D policy.

00:02:46.630 --> 00:02:50.110
So that's kind of where I got
my training in this territory

00:02:50.110 --> 00:02:52.990
was very much learning by doing.

00:02:52.990 --> 00:02:54.940
And then 11 years
ago, I went to MIT

00:02:54.940 --> 00:03:00.275
to run their Washington office,
which has been a great joy.

00:03:00.275 --> 00:03:01.900
So anyway, that's
kind of-- and then I,

00:03:01.900 --> 00:03:03.640
just as I said,
just stepped down

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:07.270
from that very
activist kind of job

00:03:07.270 --> 00:03:13.150
to this life of
leisurely MIT faculty.

00:03:13.150 --> 00:03:15.130
Supposedly, I'm quasi retired.

00:03:15.130 --> 00:03:15.760
I doubt it.

00:03:18.310 --> 00:03:22.210
But anyway, that's
my background.

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:24.632
Let me just say a
few things about how

00:03:24.632 --> 00:03:25.840
this course is going to work.

00:03:28.990 --> 00:03:34.270
We know from a lot of studies,
that MIT's online crowd is now

00:03:34.270 --> 00:03:38.200
doing about learning science,
that the talking head is not

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:40.460
an efficient way to learn.

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:45.548
So we really need you all
participating in a class

00:03:45.548 --> 00:03:46.840
and coming into the discussion.

00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:50.140
So to further that--

00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:53.192
and you saw my email kind
of introducing the course

00:03:53.192 --> 00:03:55.150
and you've seen the
discussion in the syllabus.

00:03:55.150 --> 00:03:58.875
Those of you who haven't been
able to get online yet, stick

00:03:58.875 --> 00:04:00.820
around after class and
let's make sure you get

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:03.070
registered and get access
to the online materials

00:04:03.070 --> 00:04:04.278
and the background materials.

00:04:04.278 --> 00:04:07.540
So let's talk for a few
minutes after class.

00:04:07.540 --> 00:04:13.180
But essentially, we're going to
use a discussion leader system.

00:04:13.180 --> 00:04:18.399
And what that means is that
we'll all have five readings

00:04:18.399 --> 00:04:20.440
or so for each class.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:25.510
And I'm going to ask all
of you to do those readings

00:04:25.510 --> 00:04:28.330
and then do a short--

00:04:28.330 --> 00:04:29.890
doesn't need to be
more than a page.

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:32.650
It shouldn't really be more
than a page and a half--

00:04:32.650 --> 00:04:36.460
some key bullet points
on the key findings

00:04:36.460 --> 00:04:38.740
that you drew from
those readings

00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:41.680
and a couple of questions.

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:43.750
So that kind of gets
all of you thinking

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:46.570
about the readings on the way
in and some cute questions

00:04:46.570 --> 00:04:48.430
you've got about the
readings so that you

00:04:48.430 --> 00:04:50.260
can help own the class.

00:04:50.260 --> 00:04:52.900
Because it only works
if you all own it.

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:55.450
And then, in turn, we'll do
this discussion leader thing.

00:04:55.450 --> 00:05:00.190
So each week, I'll
ask a couple of you

00:05:00.190 --> 00:05:04.420
to be leaders of the
Q&A part of the class.

00:05:04.420 --> 00:05:06.280
So here's how it will work.

00:05:06.280 --> 00:05:09.820
So I'll talk about any given
reading for maybe 10 minutes,

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:12.160
maybe a little more than that.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:15.490
And then I'm going to turn it
over to the discussion leader

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:20.780
to kind of bring you all into
the review of the reading

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:22.850
so that you get to
participate in this

00:05:22.850 --> 00:05:25.910
and get your thoughts
out on the table.

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:28.820
And importantly, in terms
of your learning process,

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:32.330
your thinking, your learning,
your speaking, all of those

00:05:32.330 --> 00:05:34.250
are key to the learning process.

00:05:34.250 --> 00:05:37.310
One thing which we know
from MIT's online classes

00:05:37.310 --> 00:05:41.300
and the learning science work
that's been going with them,

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:46.550
is that the human memory fades
after more than 10 minutes

00:05:46.550 --> 00:05:47.600
of the talking head.

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:51.260
I mean, it is just
not rememberable.

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:53.720
And it's very important to
change settings after that.

00:05:53.720 --> 00:05:56.780
So we're going to
change settings,

00:05:56.780 --> 00:05:58.402
and it's going to
be you, and you all

00:05:58.402 --> 00:06:00.110
are going to kind of
lead the next phase,

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:01.693
and then we'll go
to the next reading.

00:06:01.693 --> 00:06:03.902
After we've talked about
the initial one for a while,

00:06:03.902 --> 00:06:06.110
we'll go to the next reading,
and follow this pattern

00:06:06.110 --> 00:06:07.070
through.

00:06:07.070 --> 00:06:10.980
And then I will always
try to summarize, either

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:13.610
at the beginning of the end
of the class, where we are,

00:06:13.610 --> 00:06:16.100
because we also know that
repetition is key to learning,

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:17.127
too.

00:06:17.127 --> 00:06:19.710
So just a few elementary points
about learning science-- there

00:06:19.710 --> 00:06:22.250
really is, actually,
some design here.

00:06:22.250 --> 00:06:24.920
The discussion leader stuff
is going to be very informal.

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:26.480
This is going to
be very relaxed.

00:06:26.480 --> 00:06:28.820
I don't want you to be
concerned about having

00:06:28.820 --> 00:06:32.350
to do fancy presentations.

00:06:32.350 --> 00:06:37.250
Just speak for a few minutes
about some key things

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:39.230
that you found about
the particular reading,

00:06:39.230 --> 00:06:41.420
and then try and draw
out your classmates.

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:44.870
Now, you'll get their
one-pagers, their reading

00:06:44.870 --> 00:06:46.250
summaries, in advance.

00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:49.100
They'll get you get you
those the day in advance.

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:51.350
I'll get a copy, too.

00:06:51.350 --> 00:06:54.350
So I'm going to set up a
rough discussion leader

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:55.880
agenda for the
first few classes,

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:58.213
and then we'll formalize
it for the whole class.

00:06:58.213 --> 00:07:00.380
But all of you will be
discussion leaders, probably,

00:07:00.380 --> 00:07:03.020
at least a couple of times.

00:07:03.020 --> 00:07:05.983
But again, it's very
relaxed, it's very informal.

00:07:05.983 --> 00:07:08.150
And we're just going to be
sitting around the table,

00:07:08.150 --> 00:07:10.030
and I want you to
kind of really work

00:07:10.030 --> 00:07:15.260
to bring your classmates
into the talking.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:18.710
So questions about this?

00:07:18.710 --> 00:07:21.920
Let me talk about where
this class is going to go,

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:25.250
so you get a sense of the
pieces that lie ahead.

00:07:28.970 --> 00:07:34.110
So the first couple of classes
are really introductory.

00:07:34.110 --> 00:07:38.510
And today's class,
as those of you

00:07:38.510 --> 00:07:42.430
who were able to
get to the site saw,

00:07:42.430 --> 00:07:47.510
is really about economic growth
theory, so innovation growth

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:49.630
theory.

00:07:49.630 --> 00:07:50.840
And that's foundational.

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:54.650
In other words, what
are the pillars on which

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:56.240
studying innovation rests?

00:07:56.240 --> 00:07:58.250
Clearly, the economic
justification

00:07:58.250 --> 00:08:01.640
is one of the absolute central
and probably the critical one.

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:04.980
So what does innovation
growth policy--

00:08:04.980 --> 00:08:06.890
how does it think,
how is it organized?

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:13.070
And we're going to be reading
two very famous growth

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:15.830
economists and
talking about that--

00:08:15.830 --> 00:08:18.470
three, actually,
and kind of trying

00:08:18.470 --> 00:08:20.990
to put together the
basics of growth theory

00:08:20.990 --> 00:08:23.850
so that we understand
that and can use that.

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:32.090
And the second class moves
into kind of a second part

00:08:32.090 --> 00:08:34.710
of growth theory.

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:38.799
And we could call this
innovation systems.

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:44.768
In other words, innovation
occurs in a system,

00:08:44.768 --> 00:08:47.060
and you have to understand
the elements in that system.

00:08:47.060 --> 00:08:48.768
So we're going to talk
about that systems

00:08:48.768 --> 00:08:52.000
approach in next week's class.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.580
And then I'll give you two
kind of key tools to work with.

00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:59.260
In other words, based on
the first couple of classes,

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:04.390
you're going to be able to look
at another country, at a state,

00:09:04.390 --> 00:09:06.460
at a region, and
you're going to be

00:09:06.460 --> 00:09:13.985
able to see how you can evaluate
that area's innovation system.

00:09:13.985 --> 00:09:15.610
What are the factors
that you look for,

00:09:15.610 --> 00:09:17.443
what are the capabilities
that you look for,

00:09:17.443 --> 00:09:19.240
how do you assess
them, and then,

00:09:19.240 --> 00:09:21.550
in particular, at the
end of next week's class,

00:09:21.550 --> 00:09:23.620
how do you look at
them as a system?

00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:26.650
And then we'll take
that framework and we're

00:09:26.650 --> 00:09:30.250
going to apply that framework
and add pieces to it--

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:31.640
to the rest of the class.

00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:36.820
So the next two classes are
really about manufacturing.

00:09:36.820 --> 00:09:40.810
So just in case you got
the idea that this is just

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:44.620
policy esoterica, we're going
to have a very real dive

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:48.590
into some very real
problems that are, frankly,

00:09:48.590 --> 00:09:51.460
at the heart of the
political disruption that's

00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:54.740
going on now in the United
States and elsewhere.

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:57.070
So we're going to do
two classes on that.

00:09:57.070 --> 00:09:59.890
So a deep, very
practical, very real

00:09:59.890 --> 00:10:03.910
dive into a really
important and very current

00:10:03.910 --> 00:10:07.570
innovation system problem.

00:10:07.570 --> 00:10:14.200
And then we're going
to go back and pick up

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:18.200
some pieces we started with
the first couple of classes.

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:24.370
So we're going to look
hard at the US innovation

00:10:24.370 --> 00:10:27.930
system, particularly the
federal pieces of it--

00:10:27.930 --> 00:10:30.220
the federal R&D agencies
and organizations

00:10:30.220 --> 00:10:32.080
that are part of US
innovation system.

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:33.880
AUDIENCE: What is R&D?

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:36.010
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Research and development.

00:10:36.010 --> 00:10:38.190
Don't hesitate to ask
questions, by the way.

00:10:38.190 --> 00:10:42.620
Please bring those forward.

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:45.460
So we'll look at the research
and development system--

00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:48.022
[TRYING TO PRONOUNCE STUDENT'S
 NAME]

00:10:48.022 --> 00:10:49.390
AUDIENCE: You can call me Steph.

00:10:49.390 --> 00:10:50.473
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Steph?

00:10:50.473 --> 00:10:51.820
That is easier, OK.

00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:54.370
Thanks, Steph.

00:10:54.370 --> 00:10:56.290
And where did it
come from, how does

00:10:56.290 --> 00:11:00.550
it think, how is it organized,
what are its origins.

00:11:00.550 --> 00:11:05.558
Because we're at MIT, I'll give
you a lot of insider MIT stuff.

00:11:05.558 --> 00:11:07.850
Because MIT historically was
involved in a lot of this.

00:11:07.850 --> 00:11:10.660
So you'll collect
some good MIT stories,

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:12.910
I hope, particularly
in that class.

00:11:12.910 --> 00:11:15.610
But you know, MIT greats
like Vannevar Bush

00:11:15.610 --> 00:11:20.678
and Alfred Loomis will
come up in that class.

00:11:20.678 --> 00:11:22.220
Then, in the sixth
class, we're going

00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:28.480
to talk about the major policy
focus in science and technology

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:30.820
policy, which is called
the valley of death--

00:11:30.820 --> 00:11:33.700
how do you get from
the research side

00:11:33.700 --> 00:11:36.700
over to later-stage development.

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:40.220
And that's been the major policy
emphasis in the US system.

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:43.000
There's a big chasm
there, a valley.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.040
Building the bridging
mechanisms across

00:11:46.040 --> 00:11:48.550
has been a big
policy preoccupation.

00:11:48.550 --> 00:11:51.040
So we'll dive into
that literature.

00:11:51.040 --> 00:11:53.980
And we will also
look at the fact

00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:58.870
that the United States actually
runs two innovation systems.

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:00.940
So we run the innovation system.

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:02.980
Probably most of you
are familiar with places

00:12:02.980 --> 00:12:06.340
like NSF, the Office of
Science at the Department

00:12:06.340 --> 00:12:09.130
of Energy, NIH.

00:12:09.130 --> 00:12:10.870
So that's the kind
of civilian side,

00:12:10.870 --> 00:12:13.780
but then there's a whole
defense innovation system that

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:16.420
is organized very differently.

00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:18.610
Lily is nodding her head,
because we spent time

00:12:18.610 --> 00:12:20.200
on this in the first class.

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:21.940
So we'll talk about
that system, too,

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:24.950
and kind of how that works.

00:12:24.950 --> 00:12:28.090
And then, up until
class 7, we've

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:31.060
been talking about
innovation as though it

00:12:31.060 --> 00:12:34.270
has to do with institutions.

00:12:34.270 --> 00:12:38.830
But people innovate,
not institutions.

00:12:38.830 --> 00:12:41.680
So innovation is
owned by people.

00:12:41.680 --> 00:12:45.190
It occurs in a very
face-to-face environment.

00:12:45.190 --> 00:12:46.890
You can't just
understand innovation

00:12:46.890 --> 00:12:48.640
by understanding the
institutions that are

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:50.410
sticking their hands into it.

00:12:50.410 --> 00:12:52.930
In the end, it's
a people system.

00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:54.640
And how do people--

00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:58.690
what does innovation look like
when people are running it

00:12:58.690 --> 00:13:00.940
at the face-to-face level?

00:13:00.940 --> 00:13:02.910
And it turns out there's
literature on this.

00:13:02.910 --> 00:13:05.770
There are some rules
that innovation groups

00:13:05.770 --> 00:13:08.738
tend to follow when
they're undertaking

00:13:08.738 --> 00:13:10.780
their process of trying
to get to a breakthrough.

00:13:10.780 --> 00:13:13.690
So we'll look at the
organization of innovation

00:13:13.690 --> 00:13:16.210
systems at the face-to-face
level as well as

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:17.710
the institutional level.

00:13:17.710 --> 00:13:20.380
And that class, you all
will own, because I'm

00:13:20.380 --> 00:13:21.970
going to have you all present--

00:13:21.970 --> 00:13:23.590
a whole group of you--

00:13:23.590 --> 00:13:25.390
on great innovation groups.

00:13:28.690 --> 00:13:31.870
And then we've got the
foundations of set,

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:35.740
and we're going to start to
look at particular segments.

00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:38.850
So we'll take a deep dive into
DARPA, the Defense Advanced

00:13:38.850 --> 00:13:43.980
Research Agency, and
its innovation model.

00:13:43.980 --> 00:13:47.110
So that'll be kind
of a case study.

00:13:47.110 --> 00:13:54.150
We're going to take a close
look at energy technology.

00:13:54.150 --> 00:13:57.180
And here, Martha will help
us get through the class,

