00:38:04.050 --> 00:38:06.360
access to the Stellar site--

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:10.110
but just blow by the
economics formulation period.

00:38:10.110 --> 00:38:11.670
Just blow by the econometrics.

00:38:11.670 --> 00:38:14.895
Just get the basic ideas down
for both Solow and for Romer,

00:38:14.895 --> 00:38:15.540
in particular.

00:38:15.540 --> 00:38:18.060
The Romer one is particularly
complicated reading,

00:38:18.060 --> 00:38:21.570
for those of you who've
not studied economics.

00:38:21.570 --> 00:38:24.390
But he goes after
classical economic theory.

00:38:24.390 --> 00:38:27.300
And just to summarize,
in a simpler way

00:38:27.300 --> 00:38:32.820
than is really fair to
classical economics,

00:38:32.820 --> 00:38:35.700
classical economics
asked when an economy

00:38:35.700 --> 00:38:40.030
is capable of steady
economic growth.

00:38:40.030 --> 00:38:42.360
And they never came
up with a good answer.

00:38:44.920 --> 00:38:47.910
The formulation was when the
national savings rate, which

00:38:47.910 --> 00:38:50.160
means income saved
in the economy,

00:38:50.160 --> 00:38:54.810
equals the capital supply,
capital output ratio,

00:38:54.810 --> 00:39:00.030
and the rate of labor force
growth, that's labor supply,

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:01.170
then you get growth.

00:39:01.170 --> 00:39:03.990
That was the theory, all right?

00:39:03.990 --> 00:39:06.540
So let me simplify
that even more.

00:39:06.540 --> 00:39:09.330
Essentially, you've
got two factors.

00:39:09.330 --> 00:39:11.790
Capital supply and labor supply.

00:39:11.790 --> 00:39:14.220
And it's not capital
supply, like, all the money.

00:39:14.220 --> 00:39:16.420
It's capitals like
plant equipment,

00:39:16.420 --> 00:39:19.890
as well as resources,
that's available.

00:39:19.890 --> 00:39:23.250
And labor supply includes not
just the number of workers,

00:39:23.250 --> 00:39:26.490
but education health
systems and the supporting

00:39:26.490 --> 00:39:27.510
systems for that, too.

00:39:27.510 --> 00:39:29.700
So these are bigger concepts.

00:39:29.700 --> 00:39:32.550
So essentially, their
theory was that these

00:39:32.550 --> 00:39:34.800
are the contributing factors,
capital supply and labor

00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:36.570
supply.

00:39:36.570 --> 00:39:41.610
And when you get those in
the right balance, supported

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:45.390
by your national saving
rate, which is essentially

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:47.730
the funder of those
systems, then you

00:39:47.730 --> 00:39:48.960
will get economic growth.

00:39:52.180 --> 00:39:54.900
It's a static view.

00:39:54.900 --> 00:39:57.840
It's an equilibrium system.

00:39:57.840 --> 00:40:02.490
And these factors have to
be in the right balance--

00:40:02.490 --> 00:40:06.420
they constantly tend to
throw each other off--

00:40:06.420 --> 00:40:07.630
for growth to occur.

00:40:07.630 --> 00:40:11.628
So you explain a
business cycle from this.

00:40:11.628 --> 00:40:12.420
I mean, not really.

00:40:12.420 --> 00:40:15.240
But that's what
it attempts to do.

00:40:15.240 --> 00:40:17.400
And capitalism
becomes just periods

00:40:17.400 --> 00:40:22.860
of alternating improvement
and gain and decline.

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:25.770
So it's a business cycle
kind of explanation.

00:40:25.770 --> 00:40:29.100
Worsening unemployment and
then labor shortages, right?

00:40:29.100 --> 00:40:32.010
Everything is throwing
each other, over time,

00:40:32.010 --> 00:40:33.510
out of balance.

00:40:33.510 --> 00:40:34.935
It is not a dynamic model.

00:40:38.980 --> 00:40:44.160
I should explain that classical
economics basically starts

00:40:44.160 --> 00:40:49.230
with Adam Smith and
lasts until, really,

00:40:49.230 --> 00:40:52.170
the post World War II period.

00:40:52.170 --> 00:40:55.830
And the problem
with economics that

00:40:55.830 --> 00:40:58.230
was so frustrating to
economists, as well

00:40:58.230 --> 00:41:04.290
as policymakers, was
that it didn't really

00:41:04.290 --> 00:41:08.040
have a foundational set
of operating and working

00:41:08.040 --> 00:41:09.420
assumptions that were reliable.

00:41:09.420 --> 00:41:10.810
It didn't have a reliable base.

00:41:10.810 --> 00:41:15.480
So if you had 15 of you
were economists sitting

00:41:15.480 --> 00:41:19.560
around trying to explain
to me, a policymaker,

00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:23.590
how come there was
a Great Depression,

00:41:23.590 --> 00:41:26.740
you would have at least 30
ideas on the table, right?

00:41:26.740 --> 00:41:30.052
It wasn't really
terribly helpful to me.

00:41:30.052 --> 00:41:31.510
There were just
too many variables.

00:41:31.510 --> 00:41:35.410
So social science, in the
course of World War II,

00:41:35.410 --> 00:41:40.180
saw what physics did--

00:41:40.180 --> 00:41:42.370
staring at our two
physics guys here.

00:41:42.370 --> 00:41:46.210
Well, there's more--
several physics books.

00:41:46.210 --> 00:41:51.280
Physics, in that pre
World War II period,

00:41:51.280 --> 00:41:56.260
attempts to get down to
basic known scientifically

00:41:56.260 --> 00:42:00.882
established currents
of fact that

00:42:00.882 --> 00:42:02.090
can be demonstrated and known

00:42:02.090 --> 00:42:05.052
So that's the whole particle
physics endeavor, right?

00:42:05.052 --> 00:42:06.760
We're going to weed
out extraneous stuff,

00:42:06.760 --> 00:42:09.550
get down to a fairly
small subset of stuff

00:42:09.550 --> 00:42:11.710
that we really
know, and then work

00:42:11.710 --> 00:42:13.690
with those as building blocks.

00:42:13.690 --> 00:42:16.570
So all of the social
sciences watch

00:42:16.570 --> 00:42:20.242
what happens to physics in
that pre World War II period,

00:42:20.242 --> 00:42:21.700
and that World War
II period, where

00:42:21.700 --> 00:42:25.257
eventually things like nuclear
weapons and power come about.

00:42:25.257 --> 00:42:27.340
And they think, gee, maybe
they're onto something.

00:42:27.340 --> 00:42:30.530
Maybe that's a practice
that we ought to do.

00:42:30.530 --> 00:42:37.020
Can we get down to a relatively
small number of known variables

00:42:37.020 --> 00:42:39.130
and, in effect, create
a known system here

00:42:39.130 --> 00:42:41.600
that's much more reliable
than the kind of pre World War

00:42:41.600 --> 00:42:44.077
II guesswork in economics--

00:42:44.077 --> 00:42:46.660
that everybody would be working
from a similar kind of problem

00:42:46.660 --> 00:42:47.710
set?

00:42:47.710 --> 00:42:50.200
So that's the enterprise.

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:53.230
Solow is a
neoclassical economist.

00:42:53.230 --> 00:42:56.350
So he's post
classical economics.

00:42:56.350 --> 00:43:00.130
He's part of a movement,
which Paul Samuelson, here,

00:43:00.130 --> 00:43:06.340
is one of the tiny handful
of the great leaders of that

00:43:06.340 --> 00:43:11.320
tries to get economics down
to a subset of known factors

00:43:11.320 --> 00:43:15.070
and known realities that can be
demonstrated and mathematically

00:43:15.070 --> 00:43:16.580
proven.

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:19.060
So that's what neoclassical
economics is up against.

00:43:19.060 --> 00:43:20.490
That's what they're
trying to do.

00:43:20.490 --> 00:43:23.500
Solow is a
neoclassical economist.

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:27.800
And he is working through
this problem of growth.

00:43:27.800 --> 00:43:31.180
So he had, what, 150, 200
years worth of economics?

00:43:31.180 --> 00:43:33.460
And they didn't have a
viable growth theory.

00:43:33.460 --> 00:43:36.070
I mean, what's with this?

00:43:36.070 --> 00:43:38.610
So, fortunately,
Solow comes along.

00:43:38.610 --> 00:43:39.550
And he forms one.

00:43:39.550 --> 00:43:44.170
And he said the story told by
these classical models felt

00:43:44.170 --> 00:43:46.420
wrong.

00:43:46.420 --> 00:43:50.140
And he noted that in one of the
classical economists, Harrod,

00:43:50.140 --> 00:43:51.880
there was a hint
and generalizations

00:43:51.880 --> 00:43:53.920
about entrepreneurial behavior.

00:43:53.920 --> 00:43:59.830
And he decided
that he could think

00:43:59.830 --> 00:44:03.430
about replacing the
capital and labor

00:44:03.430 --> 00:44:07.090
output with a richer
and more realistic

00:44:07.090 --> 00:44:11.770
representation of
technology, which

00:44:11.770 --> 00:44:13.480
would be a new
theory of production,

00:44:13.480 --> 00:44:15.550
not just an assessment
of output levels.

00:44:18.530 --> 00:44:21.820
That's the key
thought pattern here.

00:44:21.820 --> 00:44:24.160
So it's not that capital
supply and labor supply

00:44:24.160 --> 00:44:26.320
aren't important, right?

00:44:26.320 --> 00:44:28.750
They remain important factors.

00:44:28.750 --> 00:44:34.660
But they are not close to
as important as this more

00:44:34.660 --> 00:44:37.540
realistic representation of
technology, which he also

00:44:37.540 --> 00:44:40.850
calls, as I said earlier,
technological and related

00:44:40.850 --> 00:44:41.350
innovation.

00:44:41.350 --> 00:44:44.770
So it's not just the
technology, right?

00:44:44.770 --> 00:44:47.110
It includes that bundle of
stuff around the technology,

00:44:47.110 --> 00:44:49.510
like process and business
models that enable it.

00:44:52.210 --> 00:44:57.430
But in the end, it's
technology-based innovation

00:44:57.430 --> 00:44:59.870
that becomes the heart
of economic growth.

00:44:59.870 --> 00:45:04.900
And Solow does a 50 year
review of the US economy.

00:45:04.900 --> 00:45:12.330
And he concludes that in
that 50 year time period,

00:45:12.330 --> 00:45:13.960
technological and
related innovation

00:45:13.960 --> 00:45:17.800
is the dominant causative
factor of US economic growth

00:45:17.800 --> 00:45:21.420
to the tune of about 2/3.

00:45:21.420 --> 00:45:26.960
So in that range, somewhere
between 50% and higher.

00:45:26.960 --> 00:45:28.550
We may be on the
higher end of that,

00:45:28.550 --> 00:45:32.300
now, in this era
that we're in now.

00:45:32.300 --> 00:45:35.510
And that's his key breakthrough.

00:45:35.510 --> 00:45:40.275
So capital supply and labor
supply are significant.

00:45:40.275 --> 00:45:41.525
But they're down in the teens.

00:45:45.160 --> 00:45:47.290
Now he acknowledges
that the rate of growth

00:45:47.290 --> 00:45:49.575
is going to depend upon
the investment rate.

00:45:49.575 --> 00:45:51.700
Because that will be a
factor that helps drives it.

00:45:51.700 --> 00:45:54.650
So capital supply here
is still significant.

00:45:54.650 --> 00:46:00.880
But old growth theory, classical
growth theory, is mechanical.

00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:02.067
It is an equilibrium system.

00:46:02.067 --> 00:46:04.150
It's constantly going in
and out of balance, hence

00:46:04.150 --> 00:46:06.200
those business cycles.

00:46:06.200 --> 00:46:09.550
The great thing about
what Solow comes up with

00:46:09.550 --> 00:46:14.347
is that he brings
a dynamic factor

00:46:14.347 --> 00:46:15.430
into understanding growth.

00:46:22.180 --> 00:46:23.400
I'll skip some of this.

00:46:29.804 --> 00:46:33.880
This can be very good news, OK?

00:46:33.880 --> 00:46:38.980
So economics goes from like this
kind of dark and dismal science

00:46:38.980 --> 00:46:44.350
to a way in which a society
can grow and increase

00:46:44.350 --> 00:46:48.730
its well-being by introducing
more technological and related

00:46:48.730 --> 00:46:49.900
innovation.

00:46:49.900 --> 00:46:53.050
That's profoundly good news.

00:46:53.050 --> 00:46:55.630
It gets us out of this
old equilibrium system,

00:46:55.630 --> 00:47:02.060
this old dismal science on to
what, if you can get it going,

00:47:02.060 --> 00:47:08.050
what can be a dynamic
pattern, and improve

00:47:08.050 --> 00:47:09.970
societal well-being.

00:47:09.970 --> 00:47:12.795
We can see these
technological innovations

00:47:12.795 --> 00:47:14.920
in the way they changed
society in the past, right?

00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:17.458
So we think about what the
19th century looks like.

00:47:17.458 --> 00:47:19.000
And I mentioned some
of these before.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:22.540
But you know, canals and
railroads and electricity

00:47:22.540 --> 00:47:24.220
and the telegraph
and the telephone,

00:47:24.220 --> 00:47:28.190
and more recent times, aerospace
and computing and the internet,

00:47:28.190 --> 00:47:31.420
these are all growth
transformers, right?

00:47:31.420 --> 00:47:34.180
And you've seen a
couple of these.

00:47:34.180 --> 00:47:36.640
You've seen the IT
revolution in your lifetime.

00:47:36.640 --> 00:47:39.820
And you've seen, on a smaller
scale, but still significant,

00:47:39.820 --> 00:47:44.800
biotech revolution, both of
which are still playing out.

00:47:44.800 --> 00:47:47.500
So you can get a feel for
what these things look like.

00:47:47.500 --> 00:47:49.630
We kind of know they're real.

00:47:49.630 --> 00:47:52.150
This is not just
some Solow construct.

00:47:52.150 --> 00:47:53.620
We feel these.

00:47:53.620 --> 00:47:55.240
Because we see them around us.

00:47:55.240 --> 00:47:57.310
So what's the pattern?

00:47:57.310 --> 00:48:00.430
So there's a core
technology advance.

00:48:00.430 --> 00:48:04.150
That yields opportunities
for new applications

00:48:04.150 --> 00:48:07.840
which can pile on to that
core technology advance.

00:48:07.840 --> 00:48:11.530
And then that, in turn, can
become big enough that it

00:48:11.530 --> 00:48:14.740
enters society at scale, right?

00:48:14.740 --> 00:48:17.420
And we also the IT revolution
spreading into different parts

00:48:17.420 --> 00:48:18.820
of the economy.

00:48:18.820 --> 00:48:22.400
And then that can yield
productivity gains.

00:48:22.400 --> 00:48:25.120
So productivity gains,
for you non-economists,

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:29.620
are when you're producing
more with less labor input--

00:48:29.620 --> 00:48:32.230
so more for less, right?

00:48:32.230 --> 00:48:34.780
Workers spend less time
on the production stage.

00:48:34.780 --> 00:48:36.393
And they produce more, right?

00:48:36.393 --> 00:48:37.810
So those are the
efficiencies that

00:48:37.810 --> 00:48:41.220
come out of technology, enable
these productivity gains.

00:48:41.220 --> 00:48:46.600
The productivity gains-- that
is a real gain in this society.

00:48:46.600 --> 00:48:49.870
That creates real wealth.

00:48:49.870 --> 00:48:52.250
Because you're producing
more with less.

00:48:52.250 --> 00:48:53.740
So there's a real gain.

00:48:53.740 --> 00:48:56.560
And then, depending on how
your society is organized,

00:48:56.560 --> 00:48:59.020
you can distribute that wealth.

00:48:59.020 --> 00:49:01.660
And the society can move ahead.

00:49:01.660 --> 00:49:05.930
So that's what we saw happening
in that amazing 1990s period,

00:49:05.930 --> 00:49:06.430
right?

00:49:06.430 --> 00:49:08.763
And we'll talk about Jorgensen
and the pictures of that,

00:49:08.763 --> 00:49:10.330
in a minute.

00:49:10.330 --> 00:49:11.862
Follow me?

00:49:11.862 --> 00:49:12.794
Are you with me?

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:17.570
So, great.

00:49:17.570 --> 00:49:19.220
We're out of dismal science.

00:49:19.220 --> 00:49:21.500
There's really good news here.

00:49:21.500 --> 00:49:25.310
You can do this innovation
stuff, and grow your society,

00:49:25.310 --> 00:49:28.190
grow your economy, and grow
societal well-being, right?

00:49:28.190 --> 00:49:31.380
That's the good news.

00:49:31.380 --> 00:49:36.838
The bad news is how the
heck do you do that?

00:49:36.838 --> 00:49:37.630
How do you do that?

00:49:40.807 --> 00:49:42.390
And that's what this
course is about--

00:49:42.390 --> 00:49:43.182
how do you do that?

00:49:45.750 --> 00:49:51.030
For a long time,
economists thought

00:49:51.030 --> 00:49:53.440
that this technological
and related innovation

00:49:53.440 --> 00:49:59.220
stuff was the way in which
rich nations got much richer.

00:49:59.220 --> 00:50:01.500
And that's pretty much
the way it looked,

00:50:01.500 --> 00:50:03.990
for a long period of time.

00:50:03.990 --> 00:50:07.530
But then, funny things
started happening, right?

00:50:07.530 --> 00:50:10.410
Countries like Korea, Taiwan.

00:50:10.410 --> 00:50:13.860
But then, really
importantly, India and China

00:50:13.860 --> 00:50:19.170
hit on aspects of a
technological based innovation

00:50:19.170 --> 00:50:23.610
model and began to significantly
grow the middle classes

00:50:23.610 --> 00:50:24.580
in their societies.

00:50:24.580 --> 00:50:27.960
So we now know
this is not only--

00:50:27.960 --> 00:50:29.670
Matt, this is for you--

00:50:29.670 --> 00:50:33.990
this is not only a model
for developed countries,

00:50:33.990 --> 00:50:36.900
this is a developing
country model, too.

00:50:36.900 --> 00:50:41.670
This is really important, right?

00:50:41.670 --> 00:50:50.110
So technological
progress is key.

00:50:50.110 --> 00:50:54.520
Capital is a supporting role,
but still important, right?

00:50:54.520 --> 00:50:59.620
Labor supply is a supporting
role, but still important.

00:50:59.620 --> 00:51:05.740
And Solow brings us this
whole new set of ideas.

00:51:05.740 --> 00:51:07.090
But then he runs into a problem.

00:51:07.090 --> 00:51:09.700
Because remember, he's a
neoclassical economist.

00:51:09.700 --> 00:51:12.190
He wants to get down to a
small number of variables

00:51:12.190 --> 00:51:15.460
that you really know, right?

00:51:15.460 --> 00:51:20.410
Good luck with trying to
understand an innovation system

00:51:20.410 --> 00:51:24.340
based upon mathematically proven
small numbers of variables.

00:51:24.340 --> 00:51:28.210
It is much too rich
and complex a system.

00:51:28.210 --> 00:51:30.280
You can't put an
innovation system

00:51:30.280 --> 00:51:33.200
into supply and demand curves.

00:51:33.200 --> 00:51:37.690
So Solow sees the power
of technological advance.

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:42.080
But he doesn't see
how to measure it.

00:51:42.080 --> 00:51:49.000
So he can't put it into his
neoclassical economic model.

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:53.650
So he treats technological
innovation as Exogenous--

00:51:53.650 --> 00:51:58.600
outside of the economic
analytical modeling

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:02.020
process that he's involved in.

00:52:02.020 --> 00:52:05.320
That's pretty amazing,
when you think about it.

00:52:05.320 --> 00:52:07.990
This guy figures out the
dominant causative factor

00:52:07.990 --> 00:52:09.640
of growth, which
is, needless to say,

00:52:09.640 --> 00:52:12.550
a pretty important
thing in economics.

00:52:12.550 --> 00:52:15.070
And then he can't
play with it, right?

00:52:15.070 --> 00:52:18.190
Because it's outside his system.

00:52:18.190 --> 00:52:25.130
So that brings us
to this character.

00:52:25.130 --> 00:52:28.360
And this is Paul Romer.

00:52:28.360 --> 00:52:34.900
And you can see, you know,
very California, right?

00:52:34.900 --> 00:52:42.310
And he's got that laid-back kind
of relaxed look in his eyes.

00:52:42.310 --> 00:52:49.390
And he is a remarkable figure.

00:52:49.390 --> 00:52:54.220
He is a maverick
troublemaker, all right?

00:52:54.220 --> 00:52:57.340
You know, I got to know
him by actually working

00:52:57.340 --> 00:52:59.830
on some legislation
with him, back when

00:52:59.830 --> 00:53:01.120
I was working in the Senate.

00:53:01.120 --> 00:53:09.210
And we knew we needed to improve
the STEM, education science

00:53:09.210 --> 00:53:12.210
and technology,
work base that was

00:53:12.210 --> 00:53:14.040
going to be pretty
important for reasons

00:53:14.040 --> 00:53:15.660
I'll explain in a minute.

00:53:15.660 --> 00:53:18.180
And how would you
do that, right?

00:53:18.180 --> 00:53:19.890
So I'm a senate staffer.

00:53:19.890 --> 00:53:22.650
I'm thinking, gee,
we're already spending,

00:53:22.650 --> 00:53:25.950
you know, X billions of dollars
on fellowships for you guys.

00:53:25.950 --> 00:53:30.420
And we're going to have to
find billions more and increase

00:53:30.420 --> 00:53:31.915
the number and expand the base.

00:53:31.915 --> 00:53:33.540
And it's going to be
incredibly costly.

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:36.390
And I'll never get this passed.

00:53:36.390 --> 00:53:39.175
So Romer is thinking
about all this stuff

00:53:39.175 --> 00:53:40.050
and writing about it.

00:53:40.050 --> 00:53:43.440
And we'll read something else
of his late in the class.

00:53:43.440 --> 00:53:45.180
But I sat down with him.

00:53:45.180 --> 00:53:50.000
And he said, Bill, you're not
thinking about this right.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:53.310
He said, think
like an economist.

00:53:53.310 --> 00:53:57.200
He said, you don't have
to subsidize everything.

00:53:57.200 --> 00:54:00.140
You just bribe the gatekeepers.

00:54:00.140 --> 00:54:01.580
That was his phrase.

00:54:01.580 --> 00:54:03.710
And his point was,
you don't have

00:54:03.710 --> 00:54:05.930
to throw a huge amount
of money and build up

00:54:05.930 --> 00:54:08.060
all kinds of
programmatic elements.

00:54:08.060 --> 00:54:11.330
You just figure out who's
not doing their job,

00:54:11.330 --> 00:54:13.790
and expanding the number
of scientists and engineers

00:54:13.790 --> 00:54:14.990
studying at universities.

00:54:14.990 --> 00:54:16.850
And you bribe them
to change their ways.

00:54:16.850 --> 00:54:18.560
That's the way you
do it, all right?

00:54:18.560 --> 00:54:20.240
Much cheaper.

00:54:20.240 --> 00:54:21.950
And sure enough, we
fashion legislation

00:54:21.950 --> 00:54:23.947
and eventually get it passed.

00:54:23.947 --> 00:54:25.530
I'm not sure it
changed all that much.

00:54:25.530 --> 00:54:28.010
But it was a fun exercise
working with him.

00:54:28.010 --> 00:54:30.560
Because he definitely
has this maverick

00:54:30.560 --> 00:54:32.360
troublemaking perspective.

00:54:32.360 --> 00:54:39.800
At one point in his
career at Stanford,

00:54:39.800 --> 00:54:42.380
he realizes the
incredible inefficiency

00:54:42.380 --> 00:54:47.030
of economics education,
that his students just

00:54:47.030 --> 00:54:51.093
aren't getting the big ideas
by listening to lectures

00:54:51.093 --> 00:54:52.010
and reading textbooks.

00:54:52.010 --> 00:54:54.350
It's just not happening.

00:54:54.350 --> 00:54:59.900
So he walks out of Stanford,
and sets up his own economics

00:54:59.900 --> 00:55:03.290
textbook company, which
is anti textbook, right,

00:55:03.290 --> 00:55:05.120
and essentially
develops a whole set

00:55:05.120 --> 00:55:08.480
of modules of learning by
doing exercises and problem

00:55:08.480 --> 00:55:12.800
sets and online elements.

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:14.540
And so you don't get
a textbook, yeah.

00:55:14.540 --> 00:55:15.957
You get something
with a textbook.

00:55:15.957 --> 00:55:17.990
But you get all kinds
of online pieces

00:55:17.990 --> 00:55:20.470
that you do constantly
in getting through this.

00:55:20.470 --> 00:55:23.430
So he completely blew up
the whole economics textbook

00:55:23.430 --> 00:55:26.810
industry and has forced an
absolute fundamental reform.

00:55:26.810 --> 00:55:30.470
And then he went out and
proved, yes, my new system here

00:55:30.470 --> 00:55:32.480
works better than
Paul Samuelson's

00:55:32.480 --> 00:55:34.250
and everybody else's textbooks.

00:55:34.250 --> 00:55:35.960
Because people are
absorbing the core

00:55:35.960 --> 00:55:38.570
ideas and be able to work
with it much more efficiently.

00:55:38.570 --> 00:55:41.278
It's a whole learning by doing
problem based learning set

00:55:41.278 --> 00:55:42.570
that he brings in to economics.

00:55:42.570 --> 00:55:45.590
So you know, he just
walks out of his economics

00:55:45.590 --> 00:55:48.710
job at Stanford and does
this for four years.

00:55:48.710 --> 00:55:51.200
And now he's on the
latest of his exercises,

00:55:51.200 --> 00:55:54.230
which is, he went
to NYU a few years

00:55:54.230 --> 00:55:58.130
ago to work on sort of cluster
development theory in cities

00:55:58.130 --> 00:56:00.100
and metropolitan
areas and growth.

00:56:00.100 --> 00:56:01.130
But then he left that.

00:56:01.130 --> 00:56:03.860
So he's now chief economist
for the World Bank.

00:56:03.860 --> 00:56:06.920
And look out, right?

00:56:06.920 --> 00:56:09.620
Because there's going to
be trouble ahead here.

00:56:09.620 --> 00:56:12.110
He's going to change that
place, I'm confident.

00:56:12.110 --> 00:56:16.353
But let's talk about the ideas
that he brings to our problem.

00:56:16.353 --> 00:56:18.020
AUDIENCE: When did
he switch over, Bill?

00:56:18.020 --> 00:56:20.398
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:56:20.398 --> 00:56:21.940
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
This past summer.

00:56:21.940 --> 00:56:23.510
I think that's when he started.

00:56:23.510 --> 00:56:25.010
I haven't seen him
since he started.

00:56:25.010 --> 00:56:27.210
But sure enough,
one thing he does,

00:56:27.210 --> 00:56:32.660
he writes this attack on
economists saying they're

00:56:32.660 --> 00:56:36.650
completely in love with, you
know, metrics and mathematics.

00:56:36.650 --> 00:56:38.330
And it's not going
to get them anywhere.

00:56:38.330 --> 00:56:40.408
These systems are too complex.

00:56:40.408 --> 00:56:42.200
And it's just an assault
on the profession.

00:56:42.200 --> 00:56:44.840
Because this is a profession,
like all professions.

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:47.020
It doesn't attack itself, right?

00:56:47.020 --> 00:56:49.550
It's not polite, right?

00:56:49.550 --> 00:56:54.140
So Romer just lifts
the veil of trouble.

00:56:54.140 --> 00:56:55.010
It's quite a piece.

00:56:55.010 --> 00:56:56.427
It hasn't formally
been published.

00:56:56.427 --> 00:56:58.640
I'm not sure any journal
dares publish it.

00:56:58.640 --> 00:57:01.002
But it's definitely
circulating around.

00:57:01.002 --> 00:57:02.210
I'll try and find it for you.

00:57:02.210 --> 00:57:03.440
Because it's a fun read.

00:57:03.440 --> 00:57:05.750
It's really something.

00:57:05.750 --> 00:57:07.130
Anyway, that's Romer.

00:57:07.130 --> 00:57:10.310
And Romer is on this project.

00:57:10.310 --> 00:57:13.092
His famous 1990
piece-- which, frankly,

00:57:13.092 --> 00:57:15.300
probably should win him the
Nobel Prize in economics,

00:57:15.300 --> 00:57:18.200
but he's such a troublemaker
that it probably won't--

00:57:18.200 --> 00:57:21.920
is called Endogenous
technological change.

00:57:21.920 --> 00:57:24.640
So he's trying to reverse
Solow's exaggerate

00:57:24.640 --> 00:57:28.340
exogenous change
and make it go back,

00:57:28.340 --> 00:57:29.960
get these ideas
of economic growth

00:57:29.960 --> 00:57:32.420
back into an economics
thinking framework.

00:57:32.420 --> 00:57:34.460
That's his project here, right?

00:57:34.460 --> 00:57:37.580
And he starts on this pathway.

00:57:37.580 --> 00:57:40.340
I mean, let me just
summarize the basic points.

00:57:40.340 --> 00:57:43.310
He agrees with
Solow that growth is

00:57:43.310 --> 00:57:45.560
driven by technological change.

00:57:45.560 --> 00:57:47.060
And then he argues
that that in turn

00:57:47.060 --> 00:57:50.660
is driven by researchers, who
he describes as economic agents,

00:57:50.660 --> 00:57:53.960
profit maximizing agents.

00:57:53.960 --> 00:57:56.210
And then he looks at how
technology isn't really

00:57:56.210 --> 00:58:00.170
a conventional good, in the
normal sense of economic goods,

00:58:00.170 --> 00:58:03.530
but has its own set
of unique properties

00:58:03.530 --> 00:58:06.350
that make it really
quite different.

00:58:06.350 --> 00:58:08.150
But most important
for us, he looks

00:58:08.150 --> 00:58:12.152
at what he calls Human
Capital Engaged in Research.

00:58:12.152 --> 00:58:13.610
In other words,
you don't just have

00:58:13.610 --> 00:58:18.170
to do R&D to loosely
summarize Solow.

00:58:18.170 --> 00:58:27.860
You've got to have a
talent base doing that R&D.

00:58:27.860 --> 00:58:31.320
This whole project is to
take all these concepts

00:58:31.320 --> 00:58:38.500
and move them into an
endogenous theory of growth.

00:58:38.500 --> 00:58:42.960
So his growth model
is similar to Solow's.

00:58:42.960 --> 00:58:44.460
He's picking up on Solow's work.

00:58:47.280 --> 00:58:49.170
He sees that
technological change

00:58:49.170 --> 00:58:52.350
is the heart of economic
growth, as we've discussed.

00:58:52.350 --> 00:58:56.370
He sees that technological
change occurs, in turn,

00:58:56.370 --> 00:58:57.870
in a large part
because of people

00:58:57.870 --> 00:58:59.970
responding to market incentives.

00:58:59.970 --> 00:59:02.790
Again, he's trying to get
this into economic thinking.

00:59:02.790 --> 00:59:04.650
And this technological
knowledge,

00:59:04.650 --> 00:59:07.980
which is instructions for
working with materials,

00:59:07.980 --> 00:59:13.620
is inherently different
from other economic models.

00:59:13.620 --> 00:59:17.730
So developing a new and
better set of instructions,

00:59:17.730 --> 00:59:21.720
he argues can be treated as a
fixed cost in economic terms.

00:59:21.720 --> 00:59:27.270
And it's, therefore, a defining
economics characteristic

00:59:27.270 --> 00:59:28.530
of integration.

00:59:28.530 --> 00:59:30.570
So just for an example--

00:59:30.570 --> 00:59:32.282
and this article is
richer than this.

00:59:32.282 --> 00:59:33.990
But I'll just cite a
few examples of what

00:59:33.990 --> 00:59:37.280
he's trying to think about.

00:59:37.280 --> 00:59:42.780
A Rival Good is property that,
if used by one person or firm,

00:59:42.780 --> 00:59:44.960
precludes use by another.

00:59:44.960 --> 00:59:47.673
And a Non-rival Good
is a kind of property

00:59:47.673 --> 00:59:49.590
that, if used by one
person or firm, in no way

00:59:49.590 --> 00:59:50.920
limits the use by the others.

00:59:50.920 --> 00:59:56.670
So technology, he argues, is
naturally non-rival, right?

00:59:56.670 --> 01:00:00.110
Because it can be readily
shared and adopted by others.

01:00:00.110 --> 01:00:03.570
In other words, once
you see this thing

01:00:03.570 --> 01:00:05.130
and understand how
it works, then you

01:00:05.130 --> 01:00:07.830
can make your own
version of it, right?

01:00:07.830 --> 01:00:12.360
But there's obviously-- how
would you get rich off this

01:00:12.360 --> 01:00:14.070
if it's completely non-rival?

01:00:14.070 --> 01:00:19.860
So capitalists move to
make it excludable, right,

01:00:19.860 --> 01:00:22.170
where the owner of the good--

01:00:22.170 --> 01:00:23.910
Steve Jobs and his crew--

01:00:23.910 --> 01:00:26.850
try to prevent
others from using it,

01:00:26.850 --> 01:00:30.330
for example, through trade
secrets or patents, right?

01:00:30.330 --> 01:00:34.020
So technology can be made
partially excludable.

01:00:37.060 --> 01:00:42.070
But in the end, technology
has these, remember this term,

01:00:42.070 --> 01:00:45.578
spillover features--
knowledge spillover features--

01:00:45.578 --> 01:00:46.870
that make it pretty accessible.

01:00:46.870 --> 01:00:48.520
Because you get to
see the technology.

01:00:48.520 --> 01:00:51.580
And you can derive ideas
about how it's put together.

01:00:51.580 --> 01:00:55.300
So technology is unlike any
other kind of economic good.

01:00:55.300 --> 01:00:58.210
Because it can be
both excludable

01:00:58.210 --> 01:01:03.100
and non-excludable, rival
and non rival, right?

01:01:03.100 --> 01:01:04.750
It's not like anything else.

01:01:04.750 --> 01:01:07.085
It's not like owning
a farm, right?

01:01:07.085 --> 01:01:07.960
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:07.960 --> 01:01:08.990
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: And you are?

01:01:08.990 --> 01:01:09.640
AUDIENCE: Max.

01:01:09.640 --> 01:01:10.390
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Max, good.

01:01:10.390 --> 01:01:12.557
AUDIENCE: This is saying
that technology just really

01:01:12.557 --> 01:01:15.290
specific technology or
technology in general?

01:01:15.290 --> 01:01:17.770
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Technology, in general.

01:01:17.770 --> 01:01:19.930
So he's developing a
broader way of looking

01:01:19.930 --> 01:01:21.400
at this whole category.

01:01:23.780 --> 01:01:24.280
All right.

01:01:24.280 --> 01:01:26.620
So that's one core idea.

01:01:26.620 --> 01:01:29.350
Let's try and develop
theories of economics

01:01:29.350 --> 01:01:31.840
by which we can better
describe what technology is,

01:01:31.840 --> 01:01:34.240
since it's so key to growth.

01:01:34.240 --> 01:01:36.280
But his really
important contribution

01:01:36.280 --> 01:01:39.170
is around the role
of human capital.

01:01:39.170 --> 01:01:42.730
And that's what I want you
to really remember today.

01:01:46.880 --> 01:01:47.840
How can I explain this?

01:01:51.340 --> 01:01:55.900
So it's Rome-- whatever it is--

01:01:55.900 --> 01:01:57.270
200, right?

01:01:57.270 --> 01:01:58.650
It's Rome.

01:01:58.650 --> 01:02:06.690
And Romans, they're
terrific engineers.

01:02:06.690 --> 01:02:10.080
They figured out
these amazing roads.

01:02:10.080 --> 01:02:12.120
And they stuck them
around all over Europe.

01:02:12.120 --> 01:02:14.460
And that's a technology advance.

01:02:14.460 --> 01:02:17.040
And it improves communication
systems and transport.

01:02:17.040 --> 01:02:22.860
So it's a technological advance
that carries with it some gain.

01:02:22.860 --> 01:02:28.440
Now the width of the Roman road
is the defining characteristic

01:02:28.440 --> 01:02:32.640
of the width of
railroads, right?

01:02:32.640 --> 01:02:34.590
That's the distance
between the rails

01:02:34.590 --> 01:02:37.410
is defined by the
Roman road distances,

01:02:37.410 --> 01:02:40.020
interestingly, enough.

01:02:40.020 --> 01:02:47.750
The Romans had a very primitive
kind of toy steam engine

01:02:47.750 --> 01:02:51.200
that Roman kids would play with.

01:02:51.200 --> 01:02:55.080
And it had an axle
and had this little--

01:02:55.080 --> 01:02:57.050
you heat it up with a
candle or something.

01:02:57.050 --> 01:03:00.530
And then this little thing
would spin around, puffing away.

01:03:00.530 --> 01:03:03.380
Because you know, water
would boil, and so forth.

01:03:03.380 --> 01:03:05.870
And it would sort
of spin around.

01:03:05.870 --> 01:03:13.150
Romer would say that the
reason why Romans didn't

01:03:13.150 --> 01:03:16.000
take the step of putting
rails on their roads

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:19.480
and sticking the steam
engines on the rails

01:03:19.480 --> 01:03:23.170
was that they did not have
enough human capital engaged

01:03:23.170 --> 01:03:24.705
in research.

01:03:24.705 --> 01:03:26.830
In other words, they didn't
have a big enough group

01:03:26.830 --> 01:03:29.370
of people that were
talented and well-educated

01:03:29.370 --> 01:03:33.850
that were figuring out
how to move this toy steam

01:03:33.850 --> 01:03:36.900
system to an actual
technology advance,

01:03:36.900 --> 01:03:41.390
moving through the invention
and innovation stages.

01:03:41.390 --> 01:03:46.870
So the human capital
engaged in research

01:03:46.870 --> 01:03:49.690
was the critical
determinant factor

01:03:49.690 --> 01:03:53.860
about why they didn't put these
pieces together, all right?

01:03:53.860 --> 01:03:57.445
So it's not just doing
a bunch of research.

01:04:00.270 --> 01:04:04.320
You've got to have the talent
base doing that research,

01:04:04.320 --> 01:04:08.003
and that that will be
a determining factor in

01:04:08.003 --> 01:04:09.420
whether or not
you're going to get

01:04:09.420 --> 01:04:12.110
to the stage of
technological advance.

01:04:12.110 --> 01:04:13.380
So you follow me?

01:04:13.380 --> 01:04:16.470
So again, that phrase is Human
Capital Engaged in Research.

01:04:19.650 --> 01:04:22.770
If you lack human capital
engaged in research,

01:04:22.770 --> 01:04:25.430
you get economic stagnation.

01:04:25.430 --> 01:04:25.930
All right.

01:04:25.930 --> 01:04:27.790
Let's do another picture.

01:04:27.790 --> 01:04:28.525
Medieval Europe.

01:04:31.660 --> 01:04:32.413
Let's face it.

01:04:32.413 --> 01:04:34.330
There's no human capital
engaged in research--

01:04:34.330 --> 01:04:37.900
maybe a few alchemists poking
around in dungeons, all right?

01:04:37.900 --> 01:04:40.000
That's it.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:44.410
So is their economic
growth in medieval Europe?

01:04:44.410 --> 01:04:47.730
Not really, right?

01:04:47.730 --> 01:04:50.690
I mean, they learned something
about castle building.

01:04:50.690 --> 01:04:55.650
But a lot of it came
from the Romans, anyway.

01:04:55.650 --> 01:04:57.360
Economic growth
basically consisted of,

01:04:57.360 --> 01:05:02.730
you know, hiring a motorcycle
gang and putting on our horses

01:05:02.730 --> 01:05:04.410
and riding over to
the next guy's castle

01:05:04.410 --> 01:05:05.520
and looting the place.

01:05:05.520 --> 01:05:07.140
That's how you got gain, right?

01:05:07.140 --> 01:05:09.000
That was the economic
growth model.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:10.380
It was stealing, right?

01:05:10.380 --> 01:05:12.180
It was like piracy, right?

01:05:12.180 --> 01:05:15.580
There was no economic
growth model.

01:05:15.580 --> 01:05:20.550
So it's not until the
Industrial Revolution

01:05:20.550 --> 01:05:23.640
that you get a significant
amount of human capital engaged

01:05:23.640 --> 01:05:26.460
in research that's going
to be able to nurture

01:05:26.460 --> 01:05:28.950
these technology advances.

01:05:28.950 --> 01:05:33.720
So we have our second
innovation factor now.

01:05:33.720 --> 01:05:35.390
The first factor--

01:05:35.390 --> 01:05:36.120
Solow.

01:05:36.120 --> 01:05:39.060
And again, I'm summarizing here.

01:05:39.060 --> 01:05:42.570
You got to do R&D. Technological
and related innovation,

01:05:42.570 --> 01:05:44.200
you got to do some R&D.

01:05:44.200 --> 01:05:47.970
Romer, the second
factor, human capital

01:05:47.970 --> 01:05:51.000
engaged in research--
kind of the talent base.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:54.160
Behind that R&D system, behind
that technological advance

01:05:54.160 --> 01:05:56.640
is going to be the talent base.

01:05:56.640 --> 01:06:00.240
So that gives us two factors.

01:06:00.240 --> 01:06:06.390
And you guys can now look at any
country or society or region.

01:06:06.390 --> 01:06:10.080
And you can now say, oh, I
can start to look at that.

01:06:10.080 --> 01:06:12.740
I can look at, hey, are
they doing a bunch of R&D?

01:06:12.740 --> 01:06:15.730
And two, what's their
talent base like, right?

01:06:22.980 --> 01:06:25.530
Romer developed something that
he calls Prospector Theory.

01:06:25.530 --> 01:06:27.690
Now that's not in this reading.

01:06:27.690 --> 01:06:29.730
It's in some of his
somewhat later work.

01:06:29.730 --> 01:06:31.382
But it's an intriguing idea.

01:06:31.382 --> 01:06:33.090
And it's very simple
and straightforward.

01:06:33.090 --> 01:06:35.490
But it'll help you in
making these assessments.

01:06:35.490 --> 01:06:42.690
So Romer looks at the chemical
engineering industry in Europe

01:06:42.690 --> 01:06:46.920
in the late 1800s.

01:06:46.920 --> 01:06:50.610
And he notices that there
are two countries that

01:06:50.610 --> 01:06:56.850
dominate these early
chemical industries, Germany

01:06:56.850 --> 01:06:57.720
and Britain.

01:06:57.720 --> 01:07:00.990
They have the big emerging
chemical industries.

01:07:00.990 --> 01:07:03.690
And other countries are
doing stuff in this area.

01:07:03.690 --> 01:07:05.970
But they don't have
anything like what

01:07:05.970 --> 01:07:07.930
Germany and Britain are up to.

01:07:07.930 --> 01:07:11.610
So then he looks
behind those industries

01:07:11.610 --> 01:07:16.260
and finds that both
Germany and Britain

01:07:16.260 --> 01:07:22.440
have very strong education
systems for chemical engineers.

01:07:22.440 --> 01:07:26.400
So they are creating
a talent base

01:07:26.400 --> 01:07:29.700
that enables the
advances that they are

01:07:29.700 --> 01:07:32.190
making in chemical engineering.

01:07:32.190 --> 01:07:36.540
So the idea is you've got
a field of prospectors.

01:07:36.540 --> 01:07:39.760
So let's take it back to
the origin of the idea.

01:07:39.760 --> 01:07:42.420
So it's the
California Gold Rush.

01:07:42.420 --> 01:07:43.590
And it's 1848.

01:07:43.590 --> 01:07:45.310
It's not 1849, yet.

01:07:45.310 --> 01:07:46.770
It's 1848.

01:07:46.770 --> 01:07:51.630
And you've got
five or six people

01:07:51.630 --> 01:07:53.700
hanging around the
Sacramento River,

01:07:53.700 --> 01:07:57.950
occasionally sticking
a pan into the river.

01:07:57.950 --> 01:07:58.450
All right.

01:07:58.450 --> 01:08:06.220
Then a year later, 1849,
you've got 250,000 people

01:08:06.220 --> 01:08:08.110
sticking pans into
the Sacramento

01:08:08.110 --> 01:08:11.620
River and every traceable,
you know, part of that river

01:08:11.620 --> 01:08:15.040
system, up every creek.

01:08:15.040 --> 01:08:15.790
What do you think?

01:08:15.790 --> 01:08:18.850
You find more gold
with 250,000 people?

01:08:18.850 --> 01:08:19.899
You bet.

01:08:19.899 --> 01:08:22.630
A staggering amount
of gold gets found.

01:08:22.630 --> 01:08:25.262
That's Prospector Theory.

01:08:25.262 --> 01:08:27.220
And it's a little more
sophisticated than that.

01:08:27.220 --> 01:08:29.740
But you're going
to find more gold

01:08:29.740 --> 01:08:34.073
if you've got more
prospectors on the problem.

01:08:34.073 --> 01:08:35.740
Now you have to train
those prospectors.

01:08:35.740 --> 01:08:37.510
It can't be totally
amateur hour.

01:08:37.510 --> 01:08:39.069
It's much better
if you have trained

01:08:39.069 --> 01:08:43.680
sophisticated prospectors,
like Britain and Germany did,

01:08:43.680 --> 01:08:47.560
with the chemical
engineering sector.

01:08:47.560 --> 01:08:57.470
So you need that human capital
engaged in the research system.

01:08:57.470 --> 01:09:01.430
If the human capital
is driving cabs,

01:09:01.430 --> 01:09:02.840
it doesn't do you any good.

01:09:02.840 --> 01:09:05.390
You've got to have that
human capital engaged

01:09:05.390 --> 01:09:07.229
in that system of research.

01:09:07.229 --> 01:09:11.359
So you can then, now, make
a further extrapolation

01:09:11.359 --> 01:09:13.279
on what Romer's
thinking about, right?

01:09:13.279 --> 01:09:17.479
You have a way, now, of looking
at fundamental strengths

01:09:17.479 --> 01:09:19.580
of an innovation system.

01:09:19.580 --> 01:09:22.816
It's an R&D system and
the talent in that system.

01:09:29.718 --> 01:09:30.704
Questions.

01:09:41.500 --> 01:09:43.250
AUDIENCE: To what
extent does his theories

01:09:43.250 --> 01:09:46.430
include questions of inclusion?

01:09:46.430 --> 01:09:48.630
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Really
good and timely point.

01:09:51.359 --> 01:09:54.810
So if Romer is
right and you want

01:09:54.810 --> 01:09:57.273
a large number of
well-trained prospectors,

01:09:57.273 --> 01:09:58.940
and you're fencing
off significant parts

01:09:58.940 --> 01:10:01.860
of your society from
that prospector pool,

01:10:01.860 --> 01:10:04.295
you're doing something
really stupid, right?

01:10:04.295 --> 01:10:05.568
It's just fundamental as that.

01:10:05.568 --> 01:10:07.110
That's how simple
and straightforward

01:10:07.110 --> 01:10:09.630
prospector theory is.

01:10:09.630 --> 01:10:12.420
That's why what's been happening
over the last few weeks

01:10:12.420 --> 01:10:13.500
makes me so nervous.

01:10:13.500 --> 01:10:19.530
Because the US developed
an innovation system

01:10:19.530 --> 01:10:21.870
that worked on
encouraging talent

01:10:21.870 --> 01:10:23.390
from everywhere to come here.

01:10:23.390 --> 01:10:26.740
And it's a huge
innovation advantage.

01:10:26.740 --> 01:10:28.270
It's huge.

01:10:28.270 --> 01:10:30.690
In other words, if you're
running an innovation system

01:10:30.690 --> 01:10:34.090
and sucking in talent from
everywhere to help field it,

01:10:34.090 --> 01:10:37.603
to help staff it, that's
really interesting

01:10:37.603 --> 01:10:39.270
compared to running
an innovation system

01:10:39.270 --> 01:10:42.060
where you put fences
around your borders.

01:10:42.060 --> 01:10:43.500
Not very smart.

01:10:43.500 --> 01:10:49.170
That's why 400 tech companies
that joined the amicus brief

01:10:49.170 --> 01:10:51.030
in the case that's
being argued today.

01:10:51.030 --> 01:10:53.190
Because they understand this.

01:10:53.190 --> 01:11:00.010
So there is a huge inclusion
piece to this fundamental idea.

01:11:00.010 --> 01:11:00.673
Rasheed.

01:11:00.673 --> 01:11:02.965
AUDIENCE: Is there too many
cooks in the kitchen, upper

01:11:02.965 --> 01:11:03.470
bound?

01:11:03.470 --> 01:11:03.910
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Yeah.

01:11:03.910 --> 01:11:05.420
I don't think we're there yet.

01:11:05.420 --> 01:11:07.550
It's always an
important question.

01:11:07.550 --> 01:11:12.980
Does a society have too much
innovation going on, right?

01:11:12.980 --> 01:11:17.360
And I think we're not
remotely close to that.

01:11:17.360 --> 01:11:19.860
I don't think we're
close to that, right?

01:11:19.860 --> 01:11:23.060
In other words, if technological
and related innovation

01:11:23.060 --> 01:11:25.940
is the key driver
for growth, and we've

01:11:25.940 --> 01:11:32.780
got 2% growth at the moment,
maybe improving the innovation

01:11:32.780 --> 01:11:37.670
system might be a way to
improve our growth rate.

01:11:37.670 --> 01:11:40.460
Therefore, one way
of looking at that

01:11:40.460 --> 01:11:44.630
is to get more prospectors
on the problem, right?

01:11:44.630 --> 01:11:46.310
So I mean, that's a
simple-minded idea.

01:11:46.310 --> 01:11:49.450
But the prospector theory
is pretty straightforward.

01:11:49.450 --> 01:11:51.617
AUDIENCE: Out of curiosity,
what would it look like,

01:11:51.617 --> 01:11:53.992
suppose we did have too many
like he was saying, too many

01:11:53.992 --> 01:11:56.735
cooks [INAUDIBLE]

01:11:56.735 --> 01:11:58.610
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: I
think we're just so far

01:11:58.610 --> 01:12:02.628
away from this that it's not
really worthy of thought.

01:12:02.628 --> 01:12:03.170
I mean, look.

01:12:03.170 --> 01:12:05.000
Periodically, in the
science community

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:08.540
there's panic about,
heavens, we've

01:12:08.540 --> 01:12:12.290
trained too many
physicists, right?

01:12:12.290 --> 01:12:16.430
They're only going to be
able to drive cabs, right?

01:12:16.430 --> 01:12:19.220
That we're in an
oversupply situation.

01:12:19.220 --> 01:12:21.290
And every once in
a while, you get

01:12:21.290 --> 01:12:23.720
cycles that, frankly,
largely resemble

01:12:23.720 --> 01:12:29.600
the business cycles that tell us
that we may be at those stages.

01:12:29.600 --> 01:12:32.780
And panic hits the
science community

01:12:32.780 --> 01:12:35.420
that we're training
too many numbers.

01:12:35.420 --> 01:12:37.640
But if we go back
and think about what

01:12:37.640 --> 01:12:40.250
we've been learning
here, which is

01:12:40.250 --> 01:12:42.830
that technological and
related innovation is

01:12:42.830 --> 01:12:48.920
a dynamic factor in your
society and your economy,

01:12:48.920 --> 01:12:53.780
it is core to the way
in which you grow,

01:12:53.780 --> 01:12:58.430
then the talent base is
a dynamic factor, too.

01:12:58.430 --> 01:13:00.530
And you don't want to
restrict the dynamic factor.

01:13:00.530 --> 01:13:04.400
Because you're going to limit
your dynamism, all right?

01:13:04.400 --> 01:13:06.590
Don't shut down dynamic factors.

01:13:06.590 --> 01:13:07.310
Led them thrive.

01:13:11.690 --> 01:13:13.130
The problem science
has, it's not

01:13:13.130 --> 01:13:18.170
able to extrapolate to a larger
use of its talent base, right?

01:13:18.170 --> 01:13:24.350
Just because there may not be
enough jobs in formal academia

01:13:24.350 --> 01:13:26.810
for all of the scientists
who are training

01:13:26.810 --> 01:13:29.660
doesn't mean that there aren't
really important functions

01:13:29.660 --> 01:13:31.970
and roles they can
play elsewhere, right?

01:13:31.970 --> 01:13:35.090
So 2/3 of US scientists
and engineers

01:13:35.090 --> 01:13:38.427
are employed by manufacturing
industries, right?

01:13:38.427 --> 01:13:40.010
That's where actually
most of the jobs

01:13:40.010 --> 01:13:42.800
are, not in the academy.

01:13:42.800 --> 01:13:44.570
And yet the scientific
community views it

01:13:44.570 --> 01:13:46.280
as, oh, it's the academy.

01:13:46.280 --> 01:13:48.530
And that's where the
oversupply problem is.

01:13:48.530 --> 01:13:52.640
But maybe the key here is
equipping that talent base

01:13:52.640 --> 01:13:54.620
with a whole new
set of tools that

01:13:54.620 --> 01:13:57.480
enable them to play a broader
role than simply supporting

01:13:57.480 --> 01:13:59.240
the academy, right?

01:13:59.240 --> 01:14:04.580
Maybe that would be a smarter
talent based training idea.

01:14:04.580 --> 01:14:07.633
Maybe you give them
entrepreneurship classes,

01:14:07.633 --> 01:14:09.800
so they can think about
starting their own startups.

01:14:09.800 --> 01:14:14.570
Maybe they get business minors,
so they can do startup stuff.

01:14:14.570 --> 01:14:16.970
Maybe they get other
kinds of training

01:14:16.970 --> 01:14:19.370
that gives them additional
skill sets in addition

01:14:19.370 --> 01:14:21.800
to kind of classical
research skill sets.

01:14:21.800 --> 01:14:24.770
I think that would probably be
a better answer than attempting

01:14:24.770 --> 01:14:27.690
to restrict the supply.

01:14:27.690 --> 01:14:30.860
The historical US
growth rate is 3%.

01:14:30.860 --> 01:14:32.850
That's starting to
look pretty good.

01:14:32.850 --> 01:14:35.520
Because we haven't been
there for quite some time.

01:14:35.520 --> 01:14:38.163
It makes a big difference.

01:14:38.163 --> 01:14:40.080
You all probably don't
remember this too well.

01:14:40.080 --> 01:14:49.160
But the dynamic quality and feel
of the US economy in the 1990s

01:14:49.160 --> 01:14:51.680
was very different.

01:14:51.680 --> 01:14:55.530
The sense of opportunity that
was there was very powerful.

01:14:55.530 --> 01:14:58.910
And it was pretty pervasive
throughout society.

01:14:58.910 --> 01:15:02.990
And if technological and related
innovation drives growth,

01:15:02.990 --> 01:15:06.830
and it's key to a higher
growth rate, than the task is,

01:15:06.830 --> 01:15:08.990
not how do you shut
that down, but how

01:15:08.990 --> 01:15:14.692
do you get back to a higher
level growth rate, I'd argue.

01:15:14.692 --> 01:15:16.400
AUDIENCE: My concern
would just be, like,

01:15:16.400 --> 01:15:18.900
not too many cooks in the
