01:15:58.460 --> 01:16:02.630
But ideally, they get like
$10 trillion, $2 trillion

01:16:02.630 --> 01:16:06.280
[INAUDIBLE] So and
the next trillion

01:16:06.280 --> 01:16:09.724
will probably be, like, space
money or something like that.

01:16:12.818 --> 01:16:13.860
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Yeah.

01:16:13.860 --> 01:16:15.960
I mean, that's an
interesting idea, right?

01:16:15.960 --> 01:16:20.070
And I do think that we do
have too many empty kitchens,

01:16:20.070 --> 01:16:23.850
at this point, that need
staffing up, frankly.

01:16:23.850 --> 01:16:26.490
They need a path to growth.

01:16:26.490 --> 01:16:32.520
And getting to fourth generation
nuclear power, I mean,

01:16:32.520 --> 01:16:36.120
that's an absolute core
climate strategy, in my view.

01:16:36.120 --> 01:16:40.560
But I think it's increasingly
widespread at MIT, right?

01:16:40.560 --> 01:16:42.360
And we're not staffing
that revolution up.

01:16:42.360 --> 01:16:44.610
In Romer's terms, we're not
putting enough prospectors

01:16:44.610 --> 01:16:46.740
on the problem.

01:16:46.740 --> 01:16:50.760
It's increasingly
hard to organize

01:16:50.760 --> 01:16:55.440
startups to do something other
than software and biotech.

01:16:55.440 --> 01:16:57.690
Because venture capital
is just doing too well

01:16:57.690 --> 01:16:58.440
with those models.

01:16:58.440 --> 01:17:00.780
And look there's nothing wrong
with software and biotech.

01:17:00.780 --> 01:17:01.690
it's important stuff.

01:17:01.690 --> 01:17:03.840
So there's nothing wrong
with what we're doing.

01:17:03.840 --> 01:17:08.000
But we are not funding
other technology sectors.

01:17:08.000 --> 01:17:11.880
So we don't have a broad based
approach on technology advance.

01:17:11.880 --> 01:17:14.760
See your metaphor, Martine,
of some empty kitchens--

01:17:14.760 --> 01:17:17.970
we're emptying our
kitchens on quote,

01:17:17.970 --> 01:17:20.580
"hard technologies," where you
have to manufacture something.

01:17:20.580 --> 01:17:24.840
Because the scale up process is
much harder for that financing

01:17:24.840 --> 01:17:30.780
system to muster than
scaling up a software startup

01:17:30.780 --> 01:17:32.790
where its infrastructure
is in the cloud

01:17:32.790 --> 01:17:36.630
and doesn't cost
anything, and can scale up

01:17:36.630 --> 01:17:40.260
very quickly with very
limited amounts of capital.

01:17:40.260 --> 01:17:42.720
It's much more complicated
to stand up and do

01:17:42.720 --> 01:17:43.620
energy technology.

01:17:43.620 --> 01:17:44.860
It's a longer term project.

01:17:44.860 --> 01:17:46.980
And it's a more expensive
scale a process.

01:17:46.980 --> 01:17:48.120
So we're not doing those.

01:17:48.120 --> 01:17:50.650
So we've got GAP.

01:17:50.650 --> 01:17:52.990
And we'll talk about
this in the next class,

01:17:52.990 --> 01:17:54.300
In the innovation system.

01:17:54.300 --> 01:17:59.927
It's yielding a bunch of empty
kitchens around our economy,

01:17:59.927 --> 01:18:02.510
whereas I'd argue what we want
to do is fill those kitchens up

01:18:02.510 --> 01:18:04.343
but they've got to have
a pathway to success

01:18:04.343 --> 01:18:06.015
as part of that.

01:18:06.015 --> 01:18:07.140
[INAUDIBLE], you follow me?

01:18:07.140 --> 01:18:08.480
Does that add up?

01:18:08.480 --> 01:18:09.845
Is that what you're after?

01:18:09.845 --> 01:18:10.470
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:18:10.470 --> 01:18:11.960
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: OK.

01:18:11.960 --> 01:18:13.230
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:18:13.230 --> 01:18:14.100
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: Tara, right?

01:18:14.100 --> 01:18:14.960
AUDIENCE: Tara, yeah.

01:18:14.960 --> 01:18:17.210
